    <p><strong>Step in and step back</strong></p>

    <p>step in and step backâ€¦ For instance, if the topic is abortion, think about its ramifications on a specific 16-year-old girl, maybe an actual girl that you know. Then think about its ramifications for society.Â </p>

    <p>Each time you add a new detail to your mental construction, step in and step back again.Â </p>

    <p>This is a really useful process for artistic creation: (step in) what is the color of the grain of sand that the hero is rubbing between his fingers? (step back) What is the story Iâ€™m trying to tell?</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Think sensually.</strong></p>

    <p>Humans are sensual creatures: we live through taste, touch, smell, seeing and hearing â€“ also through fucking, fleeing and fighting. How can you tie your idea in with your lizard brain? Or how can you free it from your lizard brain?Â </p>

    <p>The more abstract your topic is, the more it will benefit from sensuality. Is there a way to explore that equation or philosophical idea via sound or color? Do it!Â </p>

    <p>Note: geeky folks in their teens and twenties have a very hard time with this. (I sure did!) They tend to want to live in a world in which everyone is a sort of Mr. Spock and the only thing that exists is pure reason. Thatâ€™s not the real world.Â </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Learn stories, concepts, and ideas that make the facts intelligible.</strong></p>

    <p>Donâ€™t memorize lots of meaningless facts and strings of symbols. Itâ€™s too hard to hold them in your head for exams. Itâ€™s also a complete waste of time from an educational point of view as you will forget all this immediately after exams anyway. X People donâ€™t have trouble remembering names and statistics of players on their favorite sports teams because these facts are meaningful. If you can find a way to make your studies meaningful to you, you will learn with less effort and more retention.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Think socially.</strong></p>

    <p>Even before you fully understand an idea, try to communicate it to someone else. Take note of the parts that were hard to explain and the parts the listener didnâ€™t understand. Work on those parts. Brainstorm to come up with sharp examples and metaphors. Keep rethinking and rethinking how you communicate, even if you feel you have come up with the perfect explanation.Â </p>

    <p>Quora is a great playground for this sort of thing.Â </p>

    <p>Note: PowerPoint is evil. When I was teaching, I forced myself to redraw the same charts over and over for each class, and I found that this process helped me refine them.
Â 
  Find people who love what you love and spend as much time talking about this shared area as you can.</p>

    <p>If you are all equally striving and finding your own path through learning this new skill you all want to share, then you will build community and learn together. (the â€œBeatsâ€. Jack Kerouac, Allen Ginsberg, William S Burroughs, all rose up as writers together by comparing notes, editing each otherâ€™s works, encouraging each other, for over 20 years as they rose up in the industry together).</p>
