    <p><strong>Get rid of ego-centric motivations. Forget about yourself.</strong></p>

    <p>Ego is the enemy. Most people donâ€™t let themselves â€œgo thereâ€ â€“ â€œthereâ€ being to certain mental places â€“ because they think â€œIâ€™m not smart enough.â€Â </p>

    <p>Which means theyâ€™re scared of getting their ego bruised by feeling stupid. Fuck that shit! That closes tons and tons of mental doors. You donâ€™t need to be smart to think about anything! You donâ€™t need to be right to think about anything! To think, you just need to think. Itâ€™s okay to fail when you think. Itâ€™s good to fail.</p>

    <p>To fully embrace this â€“ and to vanquish ego â€“ you have to give up thinking in order to prove youâ€™re right, to impress your friends and to â€œbe original.â€ Those are all core human urges, and youâ€™re never going to rid yourself of them, but try to compartmentalize when your goal is to show off or argue vs when your real goal is to grow mentally or to solve a problem.</p>

    <p>If you have convinced yourself that you never think to be right or come off as smart or win points, youâ€™re in trouble. We all do that. Admit it. Embrace the fact that youâ€™re sometimes going to do it. Know when youâ€™re doing it, and stop doing it when itâ€™s not appropriate.Â </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Youâ€™re doing this to serve.</strong></p>

    <p>This is what most helps me thwart my ego. Iâ€™m a theatre director and an author. When I direct plays â€“ as soon as I start hoping the audience will think kindly of me or be impressed with me â€“ I remind myself that itâ€™s not about me.Â </p>

    <p>Itâ€™s about the play. My goal is to serve, to serve the play, to serve the story. The story isnâ€™t my servant; Iâ€™m its servant. If Iâ€™m writing a book, my goal is to serve the reader and the subject.Â </p>

    <p>As soon as I redirect my energies that way, my mind expands.Â </p>

    <p>Sites like Quora can be great for this, as long as you use them to serve knowledge and not to win arguments, be right or look smart.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Donâ€™t ever try to be original. Kill all your darlings.</strong></p>

    <p>Donâ€™t ever try to be original. Thatâ€™s a mental dead end. When Iâ€™m working on a play, I sometimes get the urge to come up with something â€œcoolâ€ or â€œdifferent.â€ As soon as I feel that pull, I resist.Â </p>

    <p>My goal is to tell the story, not to get points for originality. Donâ€™t ever try to be cool or original unless thatâ€™s your acknowledged goal. If your goal is personal growth or problem solving, trying to be original will block you. And the irony is that, by not trying to be original at all, by just honestly working to tackle the problem, youâ€™ll wind up being original, because your work will be filtered through you, and you are unique in all the world.Â </p>

    <p>Note: itâ€™s hard to apply a negative, like â€œdonâ€™t be original.â€ When I feel the urge to be original, I sometimes force myself to be derivative. <strong>If youâ€™re ever stuck because though you know how to solve a problem, you donâ€™t want to solve it the way everyone else does â€“ because that would be â€œcopyingâ€ â€“ copy!</strong></p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Study History: look at how it was done before and use it</strong></p>

    <p>Itâ€™s all happened before; it will all happen again. Use it! By â€œHistory,â€ I mean World History, local History or the history of some specific craft - whatever is appropriate to your endeavor.Â </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Identify rigidity and fluidity.</strong></p>

    <p>What parts of the structure must remain fixed or it ceases to be whatever it is? What parts must be elastic or its not living up to its potential?Â </p>

    <p>Think of yourself as a jazz musician, improvising on â€œTwinkle, Twinkle, Little Star.â€ What notes must be played or the song gets so perverted that itâ€™s no longer the song? What parts can be improvised? Are you forcing yourself to hit nails on their heads? Are you forcing yourself to run willy, nilly between those nails?</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Switch mediums.</strong></p>

    <p>If youâ€™re thinking with prose, draw pictures. If youâ€™re lecturing, try miming. Try imposing arbitrary constraints: write about your topic, but force yourself to forgo using all forms of the verb â€œto be.â€ See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E-Prime">E-Prime</a></p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Write the fundamental, logical questions.</strong></p>

    <p>Try to figure it out for yourself, get help only when stuck. Compose your own reply first, before comparing with others, inviting expert opinion, or getting criticism and feedback</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Think in visualizable, concrete metaphors</strong>. Make Analogies</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Mind Maps</strong>. Connections with other things you know</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Ask yourself Questions</strong>. Ask Why after Each sentence. Write Questions (Doubts, Definitions, Applications) in the Margin, and Answers on the Right.Â  If you get stuck, take a peek at your textbook to get the main idea.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Explain to a 5 year old</strong> (Teach, Paraphrase). Rubber Duck. Feynman Technique</p>
  </li>
</ul>

